Throughout Bolivia blocked, the memory of a coast lost to Chile during a bloody resource conflict in the nineteenth century is still present. As is the desire to sail the Pacific Ocean, once again.
These hopes have not been so palpable for several decades, as Bolivia awaits a decision from the International Court of Justice, which will be rendered on 1 October, after five years of deliberations.
"Bolivia has the will, a spirit of unity and serenity, and of course expects a positive result," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will follow the decision of the International Court of Justice on the big screen throughout the country, hoping that the court in The Hague will rule in favor of the Bolivian application. Bolivia wants that, after decades of sporadic negotiations, Chile be required to negotiate the agreement of a sovereign passage to the ocean to Bolivia.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic indigenous president (who faces a controversial fight for re-election next year), also has a lot to say about Monday’s decision.
“We are so close to being able to return to the Pacific Ocean,” he said in late August.
But some analysts believe there is little chance that the court will rule in favor of Chile, and that little would change, even if a positive decision were made.
The Netherlands-based UN body does not have the power to grant Chilean territory, and has stipulated that it would not determine the outcome of any talks.
The fact that the International Court of Justice handed down its decision six months after the last arguments shows that the case “was not complicated,” says Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And far from favoring the Bolivian cause, the last four years may have even hurt it.
“The problem of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration,” Zárate said.
Morales’ bellicose rhetoric undermined all remaining Chilean goodwill, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to exchange, but after that, it will be very complicated to organize talks.
The last exchange of ambassadors between the two countries took place in 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodr<0xC3><0xAD>guez Veltzé, who represents Bolivia in The Hague, rejected the idea that the Court’s decision-making was abnormally fast.
Monday will bring Bolivia “an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile” and a chance to “end 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits,” he said.
Calzadilla also disputed the fact that Morales — who remains to this day one of Latin America’s most popular presidents — was using the maritime issue as a political crutch.
