North Korea declares that disarmament can under “no circumstances” be done unilaterally without trust.
On Saturday, North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations that continued sanctions were reinforcing his mistrust of the United States and that it would be impossible for his country to unilaterally renounce its nuclear weapons under the circumstances.
At the annual general assembly of the world body, Ri Yong Ho said North Korea had taken "important goodwill measures" last year, such as ending nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site and committing not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technology.
“However, we do not see any corresponding response from the United States,” he said.
In the absence of confidence in the United States, we will fear for our national security and, in such circumstances, it is excluded that we are the first to unilaterally disarm ourselves.”
While reiterating North Korea's well-known criticism of Washington's opposition to a "step-by-step" approach to denuclearization under which North Korea would be rewarded if it took steps gradually, his statement proved important in that it did not reject the idea of unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to a June 12 joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump in Singapore at the first-ever summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader, when Kim pledged to work for a “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula” while Trump promised to guarantee the security of North Korea.
North Korea is seeking to officially end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also turned down calls to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
The U.S. insists that North Korea first proceed with denuclearization and ratchets up the pressure by imposing sanctions to achieve its goal coercively, even opposing “the declaration of an end to the war.”
“Those who think that these sanctions can make us fold do not know us.
The problem is that maintaining sanctions increases our mistrust.”
Ri made no comment on the second summit between Kim and Trump highlighted to the United Nations by the US leader earlier this week.
Instead, the minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the party concerned by the denuclearization issue was South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be at such a standstill.”
Still, the tone of Ri’s speech was radically different from last year’s, when he told the United Nations General Assembly that it was inevitable to point North Korean missiles at North American territory after “evil” President Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
Trump, who had threatened last year at the United Nations to “totally destroy” North Korea, did not mince words of praise this year for the courage with which Kim applied measures for disarmament, but added that there was still much to be done and that sanctions would not be lifted until North Korea disarmed.
On Wednesday, Trump said that no deadline had been set. "It can take two years, three years or five months; it doesn't matter," he said.
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that “the implementation of Security Council sanctions must be firmly and systematically maintained until full, final and verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to stifle funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then announced that he would travel to Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was somewhat disastrous.
In July, he left Pyongyang saying progress had been made, but within hours North Korea denounced his “gangster methods.”
In a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site as well as a nuclear complex if the United States took “equivalent measures.”
According to the South Korean president, Kim is demanding the security guarantees promised by Trump in Singapore, and efforts to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard: students take rest classes
This year, Harvard University has introduced a new course that allows all undergraduate students to sleep more and fights the growing machismo trend of studying by consuming caffeine all night long.
A professor noticed that most students at the best university in the world don’t know how to take care of themselves
The course, designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the first of its kind in the United States.
It was after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning that the idea came to him.
At the end, a student approached me and said, "Why am I only told this in the last year?"
She claimed that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
First offered this year, this course explains to students the need to adopt good sleep habits to improve their academic and physical performance, as well as their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director general of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after finding that students suffered from a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The course consists of different interactive exercises.
One of the sections presents the image of a dormitory containing different objects (coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, books...) on which students click to know the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical performance and the importance of integrating a routine before bedtime.
In another section, participants learn how lack of long-term sleep can increase the risks of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus with interactive icons then invites participants to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know it won’t instantly change student behavior.
However, in our view, they have a right to know this information – in the same way that you have a right to know what the health effects of smoking are,” Professor Czeisler added.
According to him, the culture of “sleeping through the night” pride still exists, and he adds that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students make lack of sleep a growing problem.
Getting enough, good-quality sleep should be the students’ “secret weapon” to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said — even to avoid gaining weight, as lack of sleep puts the brain into starvation mode, making them permanently hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California chemistry and physical biology student, helped Professor Czeisler design this course after being one of his students last year, during his freshman year at Harvard.
He claimed that this course had opened his eyes and pushed him to insist that it be offered to the entire campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to offer all postgraduate students a similar program of study before joining the reputable institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students plan an alarm for both bedtime and wake-up time, and be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED light, which can disrupt their circadian rhythm and lead to sleep disturbances.
