Almanach: The inventor of the Geiger counter
And now, a page from our Sunday Morning Almanac: On September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today, and THE COMPUTER TURNS... was born the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger, in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity; an invention that later gave rise to the device known as the Geiger counter.
A pillar of science since then, the Geiger counter has also become fundamental in pop culture, as can be seen in the 1950 film “Bells of Coronado,” starring Roy Rogers and Dale Evans, two unlikely scientists:
A man: “What is that?”
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, it's used to look for radioactive minerals, like uranium.
Thanks to these headphones, we can actually hear the effects of the atoms released into the minerals by the radioactivity.”
Evans: “Say, it sure jumps out there!”
“Hans” Geiger died in 1945, a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name remains.
