In Palu, more than 16,000 people were evacuated as a result of the disaster.
Some essential facts about Palu and Donggala, on the island of Sulawesi:
Palu is the capital of the central province of Sulawesi, located at the tip of a narrow bay on the west coast of the island of Sulawesi, whose population was estimated at 379,800 inhabitants in 2017.
The city was celebrating its 40th anniversary when the earthquake and tsunami occurred.
Donggala is a regency that runs along more than 300 km (180 miles) of coastline northwest of Sulawesi Island.
The population of the regency, an administrative region located below a province, was estimated at 299,200 in 2017.
Fisheries and agriculture are the main pillars of the economy of Central Sulawesi province, particularly in the coastal region of Donggala.
Nickel mining is also an important activity in the province, but it is mainly located in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been hit by tsunamis several times over the past century, according to the Indonesian Disaster Reduction Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
A tsunami also struck west of Donggala in 1996, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located on the Pacific Ring of Seismic Fire and is regularly shaken by earthquakes.
Here are some of the major earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: A major earthquake on December 26 off the west coast of Indonesia's Aceh province triggered a tsunami that swept 14 countries, killing 226,000 people along the Indian Ocean coast, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: Several violent earthquakes rocked the west coast of Sumatra from late March to early April.
A few hundred people died on the island of Nias off Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8-magnitude earthquake struck southern Java, Indonesia’s most populated island, triggering a tsunami that hit the southern coast and claimed nearly 700 lives.
2009: An earthquake with a magnitude of 7.6 shook the city of Padang, capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people have been killed.
2010: A 7.5-magnitude earthquake devastated one of the Mentawai Islands off Sumatra, triggering a 10-meter tsunami that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A shallow earthquake shook the Pidie Jaya regency in Aceh, causing destruction and panic, reminding residents of the devastation wrought by the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
No tsunami was triggered this time, but more than 100 people were killed by the collapse of buildings.
2018: Major earthquakes rocked the Indonesian tourist island of Lombok, killing more than 500 people, mostly on the north side of the island.
The quake destroyed several thousand buildings and left thousands of tourists temporarily stranded.
