Red Tide Hotspot: Lower Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission indicates a general decrease in red tide concentrations in some areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the CPF, more irregular flowering conditions are reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte, and Collier counties – raising concerns of declining concentrations.
The red tide covers about 209 km (130 miles) of coastline, from northern Pinellas to southern Lee counties.
There are islets about 10 miles (16 km) off the coast of Hillsborough County, but at fewer sites than last week.
Red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations in or off Pinellas County were reported last week, low to high concentrations off Hillsborough County, higher concentrations in Manatee County, higher concentrations at Sarasota County Bottom or off, medium concentrations in Charlotte County and low concentrations in Lee County.
Cases of respiratory irritation persist in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation has been reported in northwestern Florida in the past week.
